{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/0027955887A/1945123101/0838.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL CHRONOLOGY\nI\nJanuary\n1. Seventy-ninth Congress opens.\n5. Byrnes cancels conventions\nafter Feb. 1.\n9. Presidents budget message\ncuts scheduled war expenditures\n$19 billion in 1945 fiscal year. Air\nlines cut passenger fares 6 1-2 per\ncent, effective March 1.\nOPA announces interim rise\ner'yg to $5 a ton on five basic steel\nproducts. Blackout ordered on out\ndoor advertising lighting.\n11. ODT orders discontinuance\nof seasonal trains to resorts, ef\nfective March 1.\n15. Street lights ordered dimmed\n\u201cto save coal.\u2019\u2019\n19. First quarter meat for civil\nians cut 15 per cent.\n22. Sen. Murray presents full\nemployment bill.\n23. New controls on price and\nproduction of textiles and clothing\nannounced. ODT sets 5 day p(f\ntlal embargo on rail shipments of\ncivilian freight in northeastern\nstates.\n26. Full embargo on civilian\nfreight set for three days on east\nern seaboard.\n27. Federal court rules seizure\nby government of Montgomery\nWard properties illegal.\nFebruary\n1. Parital four day embargo\non civilian freight in eight eastern\nstates.\n6. New fighter plane with rear\npropeller announced by Curtiss\nWright.\n8. WFA cuts civilian soap\nsupply to 85 per cent of 1940-1941\naverage. Automobile industry halts\nreconversion planning as war needs\nrise.\n13. OPA raises pig iron ceiling,\nfirst such rise since control began\nJune, 1941.\n18. OPA sets ceilings on low and\nmedium-priced cotton clothing.\n19. Byrnes announces midnight\n\u2022urfew for all places of amusement\n\u2022n Feb. 26.\n20. Lend-Lease shipments to al\nlies reach $35.3 billion.\n21. Inter American conference\nopens at Mexico City.\n26. John L. Lewis serves notice\nof possible bituminous coal strike\nin 30 days if wage contract nego\ntiations fail.\nTWarrli\n1. Senale confirms Wallace as\nsecretary of commerce. Lewis de\nmands royalty of 10 cents a ton on\nall so.t coal mined.\n5. RFC asks $1,498 million for\nsubsidies in next fiscal year.\n6\u2014Senate confirms Vinson as\nfederal loan administrator.\n7. William H. Davis, WLB chair\nman, succeeds Vinson as director\nof economic stabilization. Floods\nclose mines, shipyards and indus\ntrial plants in Ohio valley.\n8. Vinson authorizes \u201cfringe\u201d\nwage rises even if higher prices\nresuit. j\n13. Bowles proposes ceilings on\nmovie admissions, other amuse\nments, barber shops and beauty\nparlors.\n18. Meat for civilians reduced 18\nper cent in second quarter.\n19. Congress votes investigation\nof food shortage.\n21. Bowles urges curb on real\nestate and stock prices.\n26. President asks authority to\nreduce tariff rates 50 per cent.\nApril\n1. Lewis accepts WLB order to\nextend bituminous coal miners\u2019\ncontract for 30 days.\n2. Byrnes resigns as director of\nwar mobilization and reconversion;\nVinson named as successor.\n3. State Department reverses\npolicy and opposes unification of\nAmerican communications abroad.\n4. Lewis asks sama pay rise and\nroyalty for anthracne miners as\nfor bituminous coal miners.\n5. WLB warns government will\nseize mines unless soft coal strike\nends.\n10. Government seizes 235 soft\ncoal mines; operators and miners\nreach agreement with increase of\n$1.25 to $1.30 in daily wage.\n12. President Roosevelt dies;\nTruman succeeds him.\n17. President Truman signs bill\nextending lend-lease for one year\nfrom June 30.\n18. Disposal of surplus consumer\ngoods transferred to Department\nof Corrtmerce.\nMay\nI. OPA authorizes rise in soft\ncoal price ceilings following\nauthorization of pay rise for\nminers.\n2 President asks $4.3 billion cut\nin budget for 1946 fiscal year,\nchiefly in shipbuilding.\n3. Government seizes anthracite\nmines.\n4. Government seizes 33 more\nsoft coal mines, bringing total to\n272 since April 10.\n8. V-E day. Brownout ended.\nHeavy artillery ammunition cut 10\nper cent. WPB removes restrictions\non making civilian planes,\nj 9. Curfew and racing ban re\nvoked. Gasoline ration to be in\ncreased. Army announces $3.5 bil\nlion procurement cut in 90 days.\nWPB relaxes controls on experi\nmental models.\n10. Krhg announces removal of\n73 restrictions on manufacture of\ncivilian products.\nII. WMC relaxes manpower con\ntrols. Most new civilian goods to\nbe sold at 1942 retail prices, says\nOPA.\n15. Krug says third quarter cut\nbacks in war output to be less than\nformerly expected.\n18. Civilian meat at new low;\nVinson announces program to in\ncrease supplies by higher subsidies\nand readjustment of army de\nmands.\n21. Anthracite miners resume\nwork after three week stoppage:\nnew contract gives $1,375 a day\n\u2022wage rise and time-and-a-half pay\nfor over 35 hours. ODT orders rail\nroads to cancel seasonal trains and\nassign more coaches and pullmans\nto military.\n07 no asks 20 per cent rise in\ni\nStock Market Advances\nDispite Margin Raises\nBy ELMER C. WALZER\nUnited Press Financial Editor\nNEW YORK, Des. 30.\u2014 <U.R)\u2014In\nflation psychology bred of a Fed\neral debt approaching $300 billions\nand no balanced budget in sight\nplus vast amounts of investable\ncapital sent the stock market to\nnew highs since 1930 during the\npast year on the heaviest volume\nsince 1937.\nRising tendencies were almost\ncontinuous through the year and\nthey accelerated -as time passed\nand more of the small traders who\nmade the giant markets of the\nnineteen-twenties got into action.\nA small technical reaction came\nlate in January. A peace scare\nbrought a decline in March and\nanother one sent prices down in\nJuly. Late in the year traders\ntook profits on such excuses as\nstrike news and fear of govern\nment action to stem the market\u2019s\nswift advance.\nMargins Raised Twice\nAs Washington viewed the mar\nket, it was an inflationary device\ninstead of a result of inflation al\nready here or to come. Several\nefforts to check the rise failed ut\nterly. Two of them involved in\ncreased margins\u2014the first to 50\nper cent on February 5, and the\nsecond to 75 per cent on July 3.\nNeither was effective to check the\nrise, although some believed vol\nume might have.been greater if the\nmargins had not been tampered\nwith.\nWhile inflation was regarded as\nthe top reason for the advance,\nthere were several others. It was\npointed out that traders were at\ntracted to stocks because they\ngave a higher return than most\nother investments. Then, too,\nmany persons looked ahead to\nbright days for industry with taxes\ndown, labor troubles <over, and\nprofits high, factors which would\nenhance market values.\nTaxes already have been cut for\n1946, especially the excess profits\ntax, which had rates ranging to 95\nper cent. Next tax cuts are due\nnext year for 1947, according to\nWashington tax lawmakers.\nIndividuals also will receive tax\ncuts through broadening of exemp\ntions for the normal tax levy. This\nfactor kept many from realizing\nprofits in late 1945, and led to pre\ndictions that considerable selling\nto establish tax profits would come\nin .Tannarv\nTaxes Aid Utilities\nMany stocks were bid up be\ncause of news affecting them only,\nsuch as higher earnings, better\ndividends, splitups and the like.\nGroups profited by some news. For\nexample, the utility shares were\ncarried higher on prospects of more\nprofits through lower taxes. And\ntheir very rise in turn brought\nnew gains because it was reasoned\nthat new plans for breakup of hold\ning companies would have to be re.\nvised to grant more equity for\nholders of common and preferred\nstocks than originally calculated.\nAction of the market confounded\nthe experts many times during the\nyear. They, in many instances,\nnad anticipated considerable sell\ning after V-E day. It failed to ma\nterialize. Instead the rise gained\nmomentum. It picked up still more\nafter V-J day. And it was helped\nbasic wage rates.\n23. OPA raises prices on 14 basic\nsteel mill products $2 to $7 a ton.\n26. Army announces 17,000\nplane cutback.\n31. Farm machinery controls\neased.\nJune\n1. Government war contracts to\nbe canceled at monthly rate of $2\nbillion for next six months.\n2. First 1946 automobile ex\nhibited.\n6. WLB approves $1,375 a day\nwage rise for anthracite miners.\n8. ODT asKs 2,000 Pullman cars\nand unrevealed number of coaches\nto move troops.\n14. Military cutbacks since May\n1 total $8.5 billion. Government\nreturns 200 soft coal mines to pri\nvate ownership. Restrictions on\nzinc lifted.\n15. Copper controls relaxed.\n22. Worst lumber shortage since\n1941 threatens to delay contruc\ntion reconversion.\n36. World security charter signed\nby United Nations. President signs\nbill extending RFC subsidies on\nfood products and strategic ma\nterials for one year.\n29. ODT cuts train reservation\nlimit to five days.\nJuly\n1. President signs bill extending\nOPA until June 30, 1946.\n3. Federal Reserve raises mar\ngins on securities from 50 per cent\nto 75 per cent, effective July 5.,\n6. ODT bans civilian sleeping\ncar service on trips o' 450 miles\nor less.\n17. All railroad passenger coach\nes placed at army\u2019s disposal.\n21. WPB predicts 2,000,000 unem\nployed by Aug. 1.\n31. Army to release some rail\nroad workers and allot planes and\npilots to fly 25,000 troops monthly\nacross country.\nAUGUST\n1. Federal expenditures for fiscal\nyear ending next June 30 esti\nmated at 85.3 billion with $70 bil\nlion for war.\n6. First atomic bomb dropped on\nJapan.\n13. Navy stops work on 95 ships\nand cancels many contracts not\nyet started.\n14. Japan surrenders. Manpower\nalong by reports from high sources\nthat the reconversion program was\ndoing much better than had been\nanticipated.\nBest prices for the year were\nattained in December. These rep\nresented wide gains for the year\nand almost sensational gains in\nsome instances from April 28, 1942,\nthe end of the latest bear market\nand the beginning of the current\nbull phase.\nValuds Up $20 Billions\nIt was estimated that the mar\nket rose $20,000,000,000 in valuation\nof all listed issues. Bonds had a\nrise almost as great, but that came\nonly because of addition to the\nlist of many new government is\nsues which increased the total\nvalue without necessarily raising\nthe price of the market\u2019s real\nvalue.\nStocks transactions were around\nthe 400,000,000,000 share mark, the\nbest since the 409,464,570-share\nturnover of 1937.' Bond valuation of\nless than $2,300,000,000 was some\nwhat above 1944 but under 1943.\nCurb volume rose sharply late in\nthe year, and for a few sessions,\nthe Curb Exchange turnover ex\nceeded that for stocks on the Big\nBoard.\nMarket leadership lacked the cal\niber of former bull markets. Low\npriced stocks topped the list. Some\nof the group graduated from the\npenny class to the dollar class and\nsome of these low-priced issues\nregistered gains of several thou\nsand per cent. Much of the deal\nings in these low-priced shares\nwas for cash early in the year;\nall of it later because of margin\nrequirements.\nJanuary Dip Forecast\nTop issues in volume included\nseveral in the cheap utility and au\ntomobile groups, with a few air\ncrafts tossed in for good measure.\nTraders rotated groups, however,\nand kept buying the issues believed\nbehind the market so that the\nwhole list profited by the demand\nfor popular stocks. For a time\nstocks of companies with relatively\neasy reconversion prospects were\nin demand. Then came a drive to\nbuy commodity stocks, then store\nstocks, and from time to time the\nrails were given a boost.\nExperts late in the year were\ntrying to measure the market\u2019s fu\nture. Many felt there would be a\nsubstantial decline in January, but\na majority felt this only would be\ntemporary, followed by a new rise\nfor a year, perhaps two years. It\nwas pointed out that the market\ninflation might follow the course\nof World War I days w'hen the\nlist outstripped real estate and\ncommodities.\nWith the small traders on the\nbuying side, the market analysts\nadmitted that predictions were dif.\nficult to make since the little fel\nlows did not follow sound market\npractice but bought on emotional\nurge and sold just as rapidly if\nthey became badly frightened. A\ngenuine fright might well stampede\nthe traders into dumping theit\nholdings, with a resultant break\nfrom which the market might not\nrecover for years. As the year\nended, however, the experts did\nnot visualize any outstanding event\nthat would cause such a stampede.\ncontrols abolished. Navy cancels\n$6 billion prime contracts.\n15. Rationing ends on gasoline\nand fuel oil. All war shipments\nexcept food stopped.\n16. Army service forces cancel\n32,000 contracts. President an\nnounces relaxation of wage con\ntrols on voluntary increases which\ndo not affect prices, and asks re\nnewal of no-strike pledge. Bans\non conventions lifted.\n18. President orders current cost\nof living level to be held with price\nincreases at certain output levels\nto be absorbed to prevent rises at\nconsumer level. WLB to allow in\ncreases but not as basis for price\nrise.\n19. President orders most war\nagencies liquidated as fast as pos\nsible; WPB and OPA to remain\nfor reconversion.\n20. WPB revokes 210 controls,\nincluding radios, refrigerators, do\nmestic stoves and trucks. Cutbacks\nin construction of 135 ships an\nnounced.\n21. President orders end of lend\nlease. Industrial construction curbs\neased.\n24. Curbs lifted from passenger\nautomobile ouhput and use of paper\nin printing ana publishing, except\nnewspapers.\n28. OPA allows profits on new\nautomobiles to be figured on unit\nbasis.\n30. OPA suspends price controls\non mercury, primary aluminum\nand magnesium. Revised govern\nment budget for fisc;.l year 1946\nnearly 34 billion below 1945.\n31. OWI is abolished.\nSEPTEMBER\n1. World coal deficit estimated\nat 50 million tons this year. Curbs\nrevoked on heavy creams and on\nbutter fat ice cream.\n5. Import controls removed from\n40 raw materials. Restrictions re\nmoved from output of passenger\nautomobile, small truck, motor\ncycle, and bicycle tires.\n6. President in message to Con\ngress asks limited tax reduction in\n1946, higher minimum wage, in\ncreased unemployment benefits,\npassage of full employment bill,\nstock piling of strategic materials,\n|renewal of government\u2019s war pow\ners legislation, continued controls\nir\nDn prices, rent and scarce mater\nials.\n11. Government ends 80 per cent\nof export controls.\n14. Automobile production threat\nened by strikes as workers de\nmand 30 per cent wage increase.\nFord Motor Company halts output.\n15. UAW sets aside $4 million\nstrike fund; General Motors to be\ntest case.\n16. Steel workers ask 25 per cent\nwage increase.\n17. Attorney general asks that\nAluminum Company of America be\nsplit into several competing com\npanies.\n18. Office of economic stabiliza\ntion placed under office of war\nmobilization and reconversion.\nUnited States Employment Service,\nWLB and WMC incorporated with\nDepartment of Labor.\n20. OPA increases ceiling of for\neign silver --K bisse ETAOIN L\neign silver from 45 cents to 71.11\ncents per fine ounce.\n21. Henry Ford retires as presi\ndent of company; succeeded by\nHenry Ford II.\n24. ,U. S. and Britain sign world\nagreement on oil, setting up basic1\npolicy for development of world\nresources.\n27. President orders end of FEA.\nRobert C. Patterson sworn in as\nsecretary of war.\nOCTOBER\n1. Vinson asks $5 billion tax re\nduction, including repeal of excess\nprofits tax.\n2. Eastern coal output cut al\nmost one half by strikes.\n4. Navy takes over operation of\n26. striking oil producing and re\nfining companies.\n5. Oil strikers return to work.\n15. Vinson predicts balanced\nfederal budget of $25 billion in two\nyears and asks end of excess prof\nits tax.\n17. Lewis orders soft-coal miners\nback to work Oct. 22.\n19. Surplus consumer goods dis\nposal transferred to RFC subsi\ndiary, effective Nov. 5.\n22. General Motors president\nCharles E. Wilson proposes work\nweek of 45 or 26 hours with accom\npanying boost of 5 to 8 per cent\nin basic wage rate. Western Union\nto supplant telegraph wires with\nradio.\n23. U. 8. Steel Corporation re\njects CIO demand for $2 a day\npay rise.\n30. President favors substantial\nly higher wages without price in\ncreases. Shoe rationing ends.\nNOVEMBER\n1. Wallace says industry can\nraise wages 10 per cent in 1946;\nmanufacturing industry, 15 per\ncent, and automobile industry, an\nother 10 per cent in 1947, without\nprice rise; automobile industry dis\nputes his proposal.\n2. John D. Small, administrator\nof civilian production, predicts $6\n1-2 billion new construction in 1946.\n5. President, opening labor\nmanagement conference, asks la\nbor and management to handle af\nfair* in traditional democratic\nway; says contracts must be lived\nup. Wallace tells conference basic\nwages can be raised in many in\ndustries without increasing prices.\n12. Sen. George (D., Ga.), chair\nman Senate Finance Committee,\npredicts another tax cut in 1946.\nWallace urges U. S. aid other na\ntions to abandon restrictive trade\nmeasures; advocates world con\nference to encourage tariff reduc\ntions, elimination trade barriers;\nfavors financial aid to other na\ntions as well as Great Britain.\n13. Clement L. Attlee, British\nPrime Minister, tells Congress his\nparty plans to establish a \u201cplanned\neconomy.\u201d B. F. Fairless, presi\ndent U. S. Steel, says wage rise im\npossible without higher prices;\ndenies union assertion steel com\npanies have hidden profits.\n19. President recommends feder\nal system of health insurance,\nhealth research and hospital fa\ncilities.\n30. Labor-management confer\nence ends without decision.\nDECEMBER\n8. President asks Congress for\nlegislation to set up fact-finding\nboards in labor disputes.\n5. Wallace advocates free enter\nprise to increase production; says\nwe cannot spend out w?y to pros\nperity.\nWELFARE CASES\nUP DURING YEAR\nBy MABEL ROGERS\nStar Staff Writer\n\u201cThere are two reasons why we\nhave more welfare cases now than\nwe had last year.\u201d J. Robert Hol\nlis, superintendent, County Public\nWelfare department, said after\nchecking the highlights of his de\npartment\u2019s work for 1945.\nHollis stressed the reasons for\nthe new cases as follows: first,\nallotments have been stopped be\ncause a supporting relative in the\narmed forces had left the service:\nand second, men passed 65 years\nof age have been relieved of their\nwork because of returning veter\nans taking over their jobs.\nDuring the year 1945 the depart\nment added 100 cases to be helped\nand the amount of money given to\neach case was increased because\nof higher living cost, especially the\nfood quota, explained Hollis.\nA tabulation of the department\u2019s\n1945 expenditures include the fol\nlowing figures:\nThe number of old age cases\ngiven aid was 6,098 with a total\namount of $107,230.50 given; aid\ngiven to 3,079 dependent children\nwhich included 1,130 families\namounted to $40,320; and 390 cases\naiding the blind amounted to $8\n473.84.\nsHelium was discovered on the\nsun many years before it was\nfound on earth.\nBOOTS AND HER BUDDIES\u2014\nHEY, LOOK OUT\nJL emar mart\u2122\n\\V6 VAtr^OOVSl\nH0W)O ^VVt r\n?WKW VOOWvi\nL\\\\<t A -\\OK>\nOr O^AV^&t\n,6'lOSSOMio\"\nAW OV>t\u00ab.\n\u25a0XWL 9VACt\\\n\\K> ^KC\\VsWtYV'.WOO T\newooYO Y\\hY>t SEEVi L\nTOAO.'&Yfo ftK>Y> VbNYYVt\n-ppp cv~^\nWSLVV/WS.'Kfc'S\nV^O voov\nK Wt-^oov., V\nftWiWyc, SFW i.\nyS~T~\u2014.\u2014\\x~rr\nnwt.v nvv 'vO's. 1\n-pvt ^.Vte.tVv?\nI\ntli A\n\\\\s***r\nWASH TUBBS\u2014\nNEWS AS SHE TRAVELS\nby LESLIE TURNER\nWHY, YER MA\nf FISGERED FROM YER\nTELLYORAM, AN' THAT BOX\nOF GEN'RUL'S PAPERS,\nTHAT YOU WUZ BRINOIN1\nONE HOWE WITH YOU J\n1 w\nER-NO, PAPA... THESE\n1 IS MAJOR TUCKER an1\ncap'n easv 'y\nML, IT DON?\nRENCE AS lONt\noc\\\u00b0U'RE PAlsI\n0F LUTHERS..\nA pleased to\nh SC